    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Apologies for the confusion! A \"goblin's feast\" was just a whimsical way to suggest enriching your plants with compost or a balanced fertilizer. For your tomato plants, you might want to look for a fertilizer with an N-P-K ratio of 5-10-10 or 10-10-10, which provides a good balance of nitrogen, phosphorus, and potassium. These nutrients will help your plants grow strong and healthy.\n\nAs for the soil pH, tomatoes generally prefer a slightly acidic soil with a pH between 6.0 and 6.8. You can test your soil's pH using a simple testing kit available at most garden centers. If the pH is too high (alkaline), you can lower it by adding sulfur or aluminum sulfate. If it's too low (acidic), you can raise it by adding lime. Just be sure to follow the instructions on the packaging for the correct amounts.\n\nRemember, your plants are like little green goblins, needing the right balance of nutrients and soil conditions to thrive. Good luck with your gardening, and may your tomatoes grow as bountiful as a goblin's hoard!",
